</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="86EC6543FFB0745DFF07FACEFC9EFA87" box="[151,812,1377,1403]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="description">
<paragraph id="CE4936C8FFB0745DFF07FACEFC9EFA87" blockId="14.[151,1437,1377,1979]" box="[151,812,1377,1403]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Includes population designated 
<taxonomicName id="09F64D4BFFB0745DFE6BFACDFDCCFA87" baseAuthorityName="Chapman" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[507,638,1378,1403]" class="Aves" family="Grallariidae" genus="Grallaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cajamarcae">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB0745DFE6BFACDFDCCFA87" box="[507,638,1378,1403]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">cajamarcae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the analysis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="86EC6543FFB0745DFF57FA2AFC99F943" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="CE4936C8FFB0745DFF57FA2AFC99F943" blockId="14.[151,1437,1377,1979]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB0745DFF57FA2AFEF0FA63" bold="true" box="[199,322,1413,1439]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Upperparts and throat reddish yellow-brown; breast paler, posteriorly with pale feather edges grading to a mix of buff and white on the belly and undertail coverts; pale eye-ring. Underparts of 
<taxonomicName id="09F64D4BFFB0745DFB55FA05FAFAFA3F" baseAuthorityName="Chapman" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[1221,1352,1450,1475]" class="Aves" family="Grallariidae" genus="Grallaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cajamarcae">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB0745DFB55FA05FAFAFA3F" box="[1221,1352,1450,1475]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">cajamarcae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the palest of all populations and separable in blind tests from neighboring populations. Short song is a slow-paced (~2 notes/sec), short (typically 5–6 notes) series of similarly shaped notes delivered at about the same frequency, which is a unique vocalization in the complex (
<figureCitation id="56CD2A4DFFB0745DFDF1F9BAFD14F9D3" box="[609,678,1557,1583]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="15.[151,250,557,581]" captionTargetBox="[155,1432,187,527]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1435,181,531]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 8. Songs of Grallaria cajamarcae: (A) long song, Paja Blanca, Cajamarca, Peru (Lane ML236890); (B) short song, Celendín-Cajamarca Road, Cajamarca (Zimmer ML236898)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954715/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Notes may be slightly downslurred or flat and often lengthen and then shorten. Long song (
<figureCitation id="56CD2A4DFFB0745DFE2EF996FDB1F9AF" box="[446,515,1593,1619]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="15.[151,250,557,581]" captionTargetBox="[155,1432,187,527]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1435,181,531]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 8. Songs of Grallaria cajamarcae: (A) long song, Paja Blanca, Cajamarca, Peru (Lane ML236890); (B) short song, Celendín-Cajamarca Road, Cajamarca (Zimmer ML236898)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954715/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) is a trill, similar to others in the complex but distinct in that peaks of the final notes rise in frequency, a character otherwise found only in long songs of 
<taxonomicName id="09F64D4BFFB0745DFC77F9F2FB14F98B" authorityName="Bond &amp; Meyer de Schauensee" authorityYear="1940" box="[999,1190,1629,1655]" class="Aves" family="Grallariidae" genus="Grallaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochabambae">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB0745DFC77F9F2FB14F98B" box="[999,1190,1629,1655]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">G. cochabambae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The long song of 
<taxonomicName id="09F64D4BFFB0745DFA11F9F2FE81F967" authorityName="Bond &amp; Meyer de Schauensee" authorityYear="1940" class="Aves" family="Grallariidae" genus="Grallaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochabambae">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB0745DFA11F9F2FE81F967" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">G. cochabambae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from that of 
<taxonomicName id="09F64D4BFFB0745DFD89F92EFD0DF967" baseAuthorityName="Chapman" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[537,703,1665,1691]" class="Aves" family="Grallariidae" genus="Grallaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cajamarcae">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB0745DFD89F92EFD0DF967" box="[537,703,1665,1691]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">G. cajamarcae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in that peaks of initial notes decline in frequency, whereas peaks of initial notes of 
<taxonomicName id="09F64D4BFFB0745DFECEF90AFDB1F943" baseAuthorityName="Chapman" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[350,515,1701,1727]" class="Aves" family="Grallariidae" genus="Grallaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cajamarcae">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB0745DFECEF90AFDB1F943" box="[350,515,1701,1727]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">G. cajamarcae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are constant in frequency.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="86EC6543FFB0745DFF57F966FB98F847" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="CE4936C8FFB0745DFF57F966FDC9F8F4" blockId="14.[151,1437,1377,1979]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB0745DFF57F966FED3F91F" bold="true" box="[199,353,1737,1763]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Distribution.</emphasis>
Endemic to 
<collectingCountry id="B6E17658FFB0745DFE7EF965FD97F918" box="[494,549,1738,1764]" name="Peru" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Peru</collectingCountry>
; in Andes of 
<collectingRegion id="0C32F82AFFB0745DFD27F966FD47F91F" box="[695,757,1737,1763]" country="Peru" name="Piura" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Piura</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="0C32F82AFFB0745DFC90F966FCC9F91F" box="[768,891,1737,1763]" country="Peru" name="Cajamarca" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Cajamarca</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion id="0C32F82AFFB0745DFC24F966FBF7F91F" box="[948,1093,1737,1763]" country="Peru" name="Lambayeque" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Lambayeque</collectingRegion>
west of the Río Huancabamba and the upper Río Marañón, 
<quantity id="090E9B2DFFB0745DFE49F942FDC5F8F4" box="[473,631,1773,1800]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.125" metricValueMax="3.4" metricValueMin="2.85" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="m" value="3125.0" valueMax="3400.0" valueMin="2850.0">2850–3400 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CE4936C8FFB0745DFF57F8BEFB98F847" blockId="14.[151,1437,1377,1979]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB0745DFF57F8BEFE85F8D7" bold="true" box="[199,311,1809,1835]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Plumage.</emphasis>
Overall plumage of upperparts, including rectrices, remiges (primaries edged paler), crown and auriculars, dark reddish yellow-brown (7.5YR 4/4–5/4) with pale eye-ring and shading to color of underparts in malar area. Overall plumage of underparts light reddish yellow-brown (7.5YR 7/10–6/10) with pale feather edgings, becoming pale yellowish-buff (2.5Y 8/4) mixed with whitish in center of belly and undertail coverts; flanks dark yellowish-brown (10YR 4/4) (specimen photographs App. 6, Figs. A22 and A33).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="9A896640FFB1745CFF07FD82FCB7FD95" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954715" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3954715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954715/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" startId="15.[151,250,557,581]" targetBox="[155,1432,187,527]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph id="CE4936C8FFB1745CFF07FD82FCB7FD95" blockId="15.[151,1436,557,617]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB1745CFF07FD82FEBCFDB9" bold="true" box="[151,270,557,581]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">FIGURE 8</emphasis>
. Songs of 
<taxonomicName id="09F64D4BFFB1745CFEECFD82FDE9FDB9" baseAuthorityName="Chapman" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[380,603,557,581]" class="Aves" family="Grallariidae" genus="Grallaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cajamarcae">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB1745CFEECFD82FDE9FDB9" box="[380,603,557,581]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Grallaria cajamarcae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: (A) long song, Paja Blanca, Cajamarca, Peru (Lane ML236890); (B) short song, Celendín-Cajamarca Road, Cajamarca (Zimmer ML236898).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="86EC6543FFB1745CFF57FD37FBC5FD2A" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="CE4936C8FFB1745CFF57FD37FBC5FD2A" blockId="15.[151,1436,664,799]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB1745CFF57FD37FEFCFD4E" bold="true" box="[199,334,664,690]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Etymology.</emphasis>
The English name reflects the scientific name and the geographic range of this species, which is primarily confined to 
<collectingRegion id="0C32F82AFFB1745CFE1CFD13FDB5FD2A" box="[396,519,700,726]" country="Peru" name="Cajamarca" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Cajamarca</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="B6E17658FFB1745CFD82FD13FDFBFD2A" box="[530,585,700,726]" name="Peru" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Peru</collectingCountry>
. The name was also used by 
<bibRefCitation id="AA674B39FFB1745CFC1DFD13FBC1FD2A" author="Krabbe, N. K. &amp; Schulenberg, T. S. &amp; Kirwan, G. M." box="[909,1139,700,726]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref22747" refString="Krabbe, N. K., Schulenberg, T. S. &amp; Kirwan, G. M. (2019) Rufous Antpitta (Grallaria rufula). In: del Hoyo, J., Elliott, A., Sargatal, J., Christie, D. A. &amp; de Juana, E. (Eds.), Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive. Lynx Edicions, Barcelona. Available from: https: // www. hbw. com / node / 56911 (accessed 11 February 2019)" type="url" year="2019">
Krabbe 
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB1745CFC76FD12FBACFD2A" box="[998,1054,700,726]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="86EC6543FFB1745CFF57FD4FFC73FCE2" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="CE4936C8FFB1745CFF57FD4FFC73FCE2" blockId="15.[151,1436,664,799]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB1745CFF57FD4FFE89FD06" bold="true" box="[199,315,736,762]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="09F64D4BFFB1745CFED2FD4FFD85FD06" baseAuthorityName="Chapman" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[322,567,736,762]" class="Aves" family="Grallariidae" genus="Grallaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cajamarcae">
<emphasis id="FC82EADAFFB1745CFED2FD4FFD85FD06" box="[322,567,736,762]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Grallaria cajamarcae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is specifically distinct based on vocal characters, supported by plumage characters and mtDNA genetic distance of&gt;5.5% with all other populations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
